    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-10-17T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-10-17T02:00:00-05:00" n="694"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d694">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.512/1434: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Counselor of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Lockhart</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-10-17T15:00:00+08:00"
                            >October 17, 1935—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received October 17—11:40 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>69. Embassy’s 62, October 15, 2 p.m. Consul Fletcher at Canton telegraphed
                    October 16, 8 p.m. as follows: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Special delegate for Foreign Affairs confidentially states that rice
                            controversy settled and Japanese warships to withdraw from Swatow
                            today.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Commanding Officer U. S. S. <hi rend="italic">Asheville</hi> [at] Swatow reported
                    October 16 that Admiral Shimamura had informed him on that day that he
                    considered that the tax controversy had been settled to his entire satisfaction
                    and that all Japanese ships would leave for Shanghai on October 17. Commanding
                    officer stated that conditions no longer required the presence of the <hi
                        rend="italic">Asheville</hi> at Swatow and that the American Consul
                    concurred and considered the incident closed.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Shanghai for the Ambassador and to Nanking.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lockhart</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
